                        <layout columns="2" ruledLines="15" n="mistara">Two columns, except for
                           Qurʾānic quotations. 15 lines per page.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq">
                        <desc><label>Script: Nastaʿlīq in black ink. Qurʾānic quotations in red
                              ink.</label><label>Scribe: </label><persName key="" role="scr">Mīrzā
                              Bāqir "Tishnah" Shīrāzī</persName></desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>Opening two pages richly decorated in typical Qājār-era style. Inner
                        text borders in black, blue, red, and gold. Outer border similar. There are
                        34 paintings on fols. 6b, 7b, 10b, 11b, 14b, 17b, 20a, 27a, 31b, 35b, 43b,
                        45a, 50b, 53a, 60b, 62b, 66a, 68b, 71a, 74b, 93b, 95a, 100b, 103b, 109a,
                        112a, 117b, 124a, 127b, 134b, 139b, 146a, 154b, and 164b.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <p>Contemporaneous Qājār-era lacquer binding with floral border and depictions
                        of court and hunting scenes on the outer and inner covers.</p>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin><origPlace>Herāt (?)</origPlace>
                     <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1848-04-16">Rūz-i yakshanbih, 12th
                        Jumādā I (1264?). The year is not mentioned, but the colophon states that
                        the book was copied at the time of <persName key="person_250281898"
                           role="fmo">Yār Muḥammad Khān</persName>, presumeably the ruler of Herāt
                        from 1842-1851. The only year during his reign in which 12th Jumādā I fell
                        on a Sunday was AH 1264.</origDate>
                     <origDate calendar="#Gregorian" when="1848-04-16">Sunday 16th April
                        1848(?)</origDate></origin>
                  <provenance>Owner's note of <persName key="person_250281898" role="fmo">Mīr Yār
                        Muḥammad Khān</persName>. <foreign xml:lang="fa">این کتاب ملکیة مير يار محمد
                        خان ... فقير داده شود بقلم صاحب بهادر</foreign></provenance>
                  <provenance>The collection of <persName key="person_196863432" role="fmo">John
                        Raymond Danson</persName>.</provenance>
                  <acquisition>The Trinity College Manuscripts are on long-term deposit with the
                     Bodleian Library.</acquisition>
               </history>
